<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="168" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,868,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,903,928]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Description.</emphasis>
The genus is characterised by a remarkable sexual dimorphism (see 
<figureCitation box="[1119,1219,903,928]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[182,1404,193,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1405,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873). 1 – 4 — male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 1 — dorsal view, 2 — ventral view, 3 — procoxae in fronto-ventral view, 4 — procoxa, schematic (Photo: P. Kment). 5 — female, holotype of Iphita fasciata Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008, dorsal view (Photo: L. Dembický; according to Stehlík &amp; Jindra 2008)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251065/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Figs 1, 3</figureCitation>
): males (
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.895" metricValueMax="1.93" metricValueMin="1.86" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" unit="mm" value="18.95" valueMax="19.3" valueMin="18.6">18.6–19.3 mm</quantity>
) are larger and more robust than females (
<quantity box="[701,872,940,965]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6149999999999998" metricValueMax="1.65" metricValueMin="1.58" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" unit="mm" value="16.15" valueMax="16.5" valueMin="15.8">15.8–16.5 mm</quantity>
), having the pronotum longer and more gibbose (especially the callar lobe), longer antennae (especially antennomeres 
<number box="[954,996,976,1000]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
are prolonged; see Measurements and 
<figureCitation box="[151,249,1012,1037]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[182,1404,193,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1405,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873). 1 – 4 — male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 1 — dorsal view, 2 — ventral view, 3 — procoxae in fronto-ventral view, 4 — procoxa, schematic (Photo: P. Kment). 5 — female, holotype of Iphita fasciata Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008, dorsal view (Photo: L. Dembický; according to Stehlík &amp; Jindra 2008)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251065/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number box="[207,249,1012,1036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
</figureCitation>
) and longer legs. In females the pronotum is shorter and weakly gibbose, antennomeres 
<number box="[1251,1293,1012,1036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
and legs are distinctly shorter (
<figureCitation box="[355,423,1047,1072]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[182,1404,193,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1405,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873). 1 – 4 — male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 1 — dorsal view, 2 — ventral view, 3 — procoxae in fronto-ventral view, 4 — procoxa, schematic (Photo: P. Kment). 5 — female, holotype of Iphita fasciata Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008, dorsal view (Photo: L. Dembický; according to Stehlík &amp; Jindra 2008)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251065/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Fig. 
<number box="[407,423,1047,1072]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,868,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Lateral margins of pronotum forming a sharply explanate lamina (see 
<figureCitation box="[1016,1119,1084,1109]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[182,1404,193,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1405,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873). 1 – 4 — male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 1 — dorsal view, 2 — ventral view, 3 — procoxae in fronto-ventral view, 4 — procoxa, schematic (Photo: P. Kment). 5 — female, holotype of Iphita fasciata Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008, dorsal view (Photo: L. Dembický; according to Stehlík &amp; Jindra 2008)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251065/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number box="[1074,1119,1084,1108]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
</figureCitation>
). Disc of scutellum basally depressed, its posterior portion elevated. Procoxae bearing a lateral process with bifurcate apex (
<figureCitation box="[1241,1343,1119,1144]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[182,1404,193,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1405,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873). 1 – 4 — male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 1 — dorsal view, 2 — ventral view, 3 — procoxae in fronto-ventral view, 4 — procoxa, schematic (Photo: P. Kment). 5 — female, holotype of Iphita fasciata Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008, dorsal view (Photo: L. Dembický; according to Stehlík &amp; Jindra 2008)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251065/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number box="[1298,1311,1120,1144]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="3.0">3</number>
–4
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1355,1399,1119,1144]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,155,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1438,155,1461]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 11. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873), male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 6 – 7 — procoxae with lateral tuberceles (6 — magnification 25 ×, 7 – 50 ×); 8 – 9 — profemur (two different views, 27 ×); 10 — external scent efferent system and middle leg (25 ×); 11 — detail of setiferous and spiniferous tubercles on mesofemur (170 ×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 11), 0.5 mm (Fig. 7), 1 mm (Figs 6, 8 – 9). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251066/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
6– 
<number box="[1385,1399,1119,1144]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
) in both sexes, larger in males than in females (in one female the apex is simply pointed rather than bifurcate). Profemora of male incrassate, provided with two rows of setiferous to spiniferous denticles intermixed with a few (
<number box="[159,204,1228,1252]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
) larger teeth, the largest tooth being situated near to apex (
<figureCitation box="[867,970,1228,1253]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,155,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1438,155,1461]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 11. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873), male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 6 – 7 — procoxae with lateral tuberceles (6 — magnification 25 ×, 7 – 50 ×); 8 – 9 — profemur (two different views, 27 ×); 10 — external scent efferent system and middle leg (25 ×); 11 — detail of setiferous and spiniferous tubercles on mesofemur (170 ×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 11), 0.5 mm (Fig. 7), 1 mm (Figs 6, 8 – 9). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251066/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number box="[924,970,1228,1252]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="8.5" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="8.0">8–9</number>
</figureCitation>
); the rows of denticles are separated by a smooth and only slightly depressed longitudinal furrow; profemora of female slender, not incrassate, but otherwise similar to that of male (cf. 
<figureCitation box="[452,592,1300,1325]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[182,1404,193,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1405,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873). 1 – 4 — male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 1 — dorsal view, 2 — ventral view, 3 — procoxae in fronto-ventral view, 4 — procoxa, schematic (Photo: P. Kment). 5 — female, holotype of Iphita fasciata Stehlík &amp; Jindra, 2008, dorsal view (Photo: L. Dembický; according to Stehlík &amp; Jindra 2008)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251065/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number box="[507,521,1300,1324]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="1.0">1</number>
and 
<number box="[576,592,1300,1325]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Protibiae of male ventrally with two longitudinal rows of small denticles, apically thickened with a single larger tooth anteapically; females with less developed denticles and anteapical tooth. Mesofemora of males with two longitudinal rows of small setiferous or spiniferous denticles in apical two thirds and a shallow longitudinal furrow in apical third (
<figureCitation box="[853,990,1407,1432]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,155,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1438,155,1461]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 11. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873), male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 6 – 7 — procoxae with lateral tuberceles (6 — magnification 25 ×, 7 – 50 ×); 8 – 9 — profemur (two different views, 27 ×); 10 — external scent efferent system and middle leg (25 ×); 11 — detail of setiferous and spiniferous tubercles on mesofemur (170 ×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 11), 0.5 mm (Fig. 7), 1 mm (Figs 6, 8 – 9). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251066/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number box="[918,990,1408,1432]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="10.5" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="10.0">10–11</number>
</figureCitation>
); mesofemora of female, as well as metafemora, meso- and metatibiae of both sexes without denticles and longitudinal furrows. Peritreme of the metathoracic scent gland short, oval, directed posterolaterad (see 
<figureCitation box="[893,1024,1479,1504]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 17" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[196,1395,195,1899]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[196,1396,195,1900]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 17. Ostiole and peritreme. 12 – 14 — Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873), male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 12 — peritreme and surrounding evaporatorium (magnification 75 ×), 13 — detail of peritreme (150 ×), 14 — detail of ostiole (250 ×). 15 – 17 — Iphita limbtata Stål, 1870, male, India: Arunachal Pradesh. 15 — peritreme and surrounding evaporatorium (90 ×), 13 — detail of ostiole (250 ×), 14 — detail of peritreme (170 ×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm. (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251067/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number box="[949,1024,1480,1504]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="13.0" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="12.0">12–14</number>
</figureCitation>
). For description and illustrations of pygophore and paramere see 
<bibRefCitation author="Zamal" box="[479,906,1516,1541]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" refString="Zamal, S. &amp; Chopra, N. P. (1990) Aaxonomic [sic!] studies on Indian Largidae (Hemiptera: Heteroptera). Journal of Research Assam Agricultural University, 11, 1 - 15." type="journal article" year="1990">
Zamal &amp; Chopra (
<number box="[684,745,1516,1540]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="1990.0">1990</number>
: 
<figureCitation box="[756,896,1516,1541]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,155,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1438,155,1461]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 11. Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873), male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 6 – 7 — procoxae with lateral tuberceles (6 — magnification 25 ×, 7 – 50 ×); 8 – 9 — profemur (two different views, 27 ×); 10 — external scent efferent system and middle leg (25 ×); 11 — detail of setiferous and spiniferous tubercles on mesofemur (170 ×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Fig. 11), 0.5 mm (Fig. 7), 1 mm (Figs 6, 8 – 9). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251066/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number box="[811,824,1516,1540]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="8.0">8</number>
–9, 11
</figureCitation>
)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="168" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,868,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,461,1551,1576]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[467,592,1553,1576]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Riegeriana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[467,592,1553,1576]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Riegeriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[598,703,1551,1576]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[598,703,1551,1576]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is most similar (especially in size of the explanate lateral margins of pronotum) to the Oriental-Australian genus 
<taxonomicName box="[687,754,1588,1613]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Iphita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[687,754,1588,1613]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Iphita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1012,1079,1588,1613]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Iphita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1012,1079,1588,1613]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Iphita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ in the absence of sexual dimorphism (cf. 
<figureCitation box="[341,514,1623,1648]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 24. 20 – 23" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1917,1940]" captionTargetBox="[241,1361,224,1899]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[230,1362,195,1900]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 24. 20 – 23 — Iphita lata sp. nov.: 20 – 21 — male, holotype, India: Tamil Nadu: Coimbatore (20 — dorsal view, 21 — ventral view), 22 – 23 — female, paratype, India: Kerala: Walayar forest (22 — dorsal view, 23 — detail of pronotum in most exposed view). 24 — Iphita coimbatorensis (Distant, 1919), female, India: Kerala: Pompa, Sabramila, detail of pronotum in most exposed view. (Photos: 20 – 22 — L. Macháčková, 23 – 24 — P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251070/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number box="[398,426,1624,1648]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="20.0">20</number>
and 22
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[528,642,1623,1648]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 29" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[166,1422,193,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[164,1423,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 29. Iphita limbata Stål, 1870. 25 – 26, 28 – 29 — male, India: Arunachal Pradesh (25 — dorsal view, 26 — ventral view, 28 — procoxae, 29 — detail of procoxa, schematic). 27 — female, India: Arunachal Pradesh, dorsal view. (Photos: P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251071/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
25 and 
<number box="[613,642,1624,1648]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="27.0">27</number>
</figureCitation>
) and procoxae lacking prominent tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[1152,1285,1623,1648]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 25 – 29" captionStart-1="FIGURES 30 – 34" captionStartId-0="11.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionStartId-1="12.[151,264,1651,1674]" captionTargetBox-0="[166,1422,193,1929]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1433,193,1630]" captionTargetId-0="figure@11.[164,1423,193,1932]" captionTargetId-1="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1630]" captionTargetPageId-0="11" captionTargetPageId-1="12" captionText-0="FIGURES 25 – 29. Iphita limbata Stål, 1870. 25 – 26, 28 – 29 — male, India: Arunachal Pradesh (25 — dorsal view, 26 — ventral view, 28 — procoxae, 29 — detail of procoxa, schematic). 27 — female, India: Arunachal Pradesh, dorsal view. (Photos: P. Kment)." captionText-1="FIGURES 30 – 34. Iphita limbata Stål, 1870, male, India: Arunachal Pradesh: 30 – 31 — procoxae (30 — magnification 32 ×, 31 – 47 ×); 32 – 33 — profemur (two different views: 32 – 25 ×, 33 – 18 ×); 34 — external scent efferent system and middle leg (15 ×). Scale bars: 0.5 mm (Figs 30 – 31), 1 mm (Figs 32 – 34). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/251071/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/251072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number box="[1210,1285,1624,1648]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="29.5" valueMax="31.0" valueMin="28.0">28–31</number>
</figureCitation>
). In addition, some other 
<taxonomicName box="[289,356,1660,1685]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Iphita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[289,356,1660,1685]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Iphita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (e.g., 
<taxonomicName box="[527,724,1660,1685]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Iphita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coimbatorensis">
<emphasis box="[527,724,1660,1685]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">I. coimbatorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[742,814,1660,1685]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Iphita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[742,814,1660,1685]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">I. lata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[824,918,1661,1684]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[932,1046,1660,1685]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Iphita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="limbata">
<emphasis box="[932,1046,1660,1685]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">I. limbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) also differ in the kidney-shaped peritreme (see 
<figureCitation box="[321,449,1695,1720]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 17" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[196,1395,195,1899]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[196,1396,195,1900]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 17. Ostiole and peritreme. 12 – 14 — Riegeriana apicalis (Walker, 1873), male, India: Maharashtra, Bhor Ghat: 12 — peritreme and surrounding evaporatorium (magnification 75 ×), 13 — detail of peritreme (150 ×), 14 — detail of ostiole (250 ×). 15 – 17 — Iphita limbtata Stål, 1870, male, India: Arunachal Pradesh. 15 — peritreme and surrounding evaporatorium (90 ×), 13 — detail of ostiole (250 ×), 14 — detail of peritreme (170 ×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm. (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251067/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number box="[379,449,1695,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="16.0" valueMax="17.0" valueMin="15.0">15–17</number>
</figureCitation>
) and all the femora of both sexes being ventrally provided with a longitudinal furrow distinct for most of its length (see 
<figureCitation box="[554,686,1732,1757]" captionStart="FIGURES 30 – 34" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1651,1674]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,193,1630]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1630]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 30 – 34. Iphita limbata Stål, 1870, male, India: Arunachal Pradesh: 30 – 31 — procoxae (30 — magnification 32 ×, 31 – 47 ×); 32 – 33 — profemur (two different views: 32 – 25 ×, 33 – 18 ×); 34 — external scent efferent system and middle leg (15 ×). Scale bars: 0.5 mm (Figs 30 – 31), 1 mm (Figs 32 – 34). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Figs 
<number box="[612,686,1732,1756]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="33.0" valueMax="34.0" valueMin="32.0">32–34</number>
</figureCitation>
). However, 
<taxonomicName box="[826,916,1732,1757]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Iphita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dubia">
<emphasis box="[826,916,1732,1757]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">I. dubia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks the longitudinal furrows on meso- and metafemora (observed in female) and its peritreme is more similar in shape to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[1188,1314,1767,1792]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis box="[1188,1314,1767,1792]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">R. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1334,1423,1767,1792]" captionStart="FIGURES 18 – 19" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1202,1225]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1181]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,193,1181]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 18 – 19. Iphita dubia (Breddin, 1901), male, Indonesia: Papua: Waris (18 — dorsal view, 19 — ventral view). (Photos: L. Macháčková)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251068/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
Fig. 
<number box="[1392,1423,1768,1792]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[151,374,1804,1829]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Riegeriana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis box="[151,374,1804,1829]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Riegeriana apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
further differs from all the described species of 
<taxonomicName box="[943,1010,1804,1829]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Iphita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[943,1010,1804,1829]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Iphita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the bicolorous corium with black transverse stripe on red background (see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Stehlik" box="[661,913,1839,1864]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" refString="Stehlik, J. L. &amp; Jindra, Z. (2008) New taxa of the Largidae and Pyrrhocoridae (Hemiptera: Heteroptera) from the Oriental Region. Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae, 48, 611 - 648." type="journal article" year="2008">
Stehlík &amp; Jindra 
<number box="[852,913,1840,1864]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="168" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,868,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,1876,1901]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Note.</emphasis>
Similar prolonged antennae in males are known in the Afrotropical genus 
<emphasis box="[1173,1268,1877,1900]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Kmentia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Stehlik" box="[1281,1436,1876,1901]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" refString="Stehlik, J. L. (2013) Reclassification of the genus Physopelta (Physopeltinae) and comments on the possible origin of the subfamily Larginae in the New World (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Largidae). Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae, 53, 505 - 584." type="journal article" year="2013">
Stehlík, 
<number box="[1380,1436,1876,1900]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="2013.0">2013</number>
</bibRefCitation>
(
<taxonomicName box="[158,263,1911,1936]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Largidae</taxonomicName>
: Physopeltinae: Kmentiini) (
<bibRefCitation author="Stehlik" box="[594,744,1911,1936]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" refString="Stehlik, J. L. (2013) Reclassification of the genus Physopelta (Physopeltinae) and comments on the possible origin of the subfamily Larginae in the New World (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Largidae). Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae, 53, 505 - 584." type="journal article" year="2013">
Stehlík 
<number box="[686,744,1912,1936]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" value="2013.0">2013</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) which, however, differs markedly in the structure of male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="169" pageId="1" pageNumber="168" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,868,2009]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,213]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="169" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1984,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">Etymology.</emphasis>
We dedicate the new genus to our dear colleague Christian Rieger, eminent 
<collectingCountry box="[1198,1288,1984,2008]" name="Germany" pageId="1" pageNumber="168">German</collectingCountry>
heteropterist and co-editor of the ‘Catalogue of the 
<taxonomicName box="[581,713,152,175]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Heteroptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="182" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Heteroptera</taxonomicName>
of the Palaearctic Region’, on the occasion of his 
<number box="[1280,1308,151,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="169" value="70.0">70</number>
th birthday. Gender is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
